<DOC><DOCNO> AP890815-0171 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1945EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     08-15 0233</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Salvador,0241</SECOND><HEAD>Rebels Attack Police Academy with Mortars, Rockets, Bombs</HEAD><DATELINE>EL ESPINO, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist rebels attacked a newlybuilt police academy Tuesday with mortars, rockets, dynamite bombsand rifle fire, wounding two policemen and five cadets, authoritiesreported.   The attack, which began with a mortar barrage early Tuesday,awakened residents in El Espino, located just west of San Salvador,and two nearby communities.   A rebel spokesman telephoned local radio stations and said 25guerrillas carried out the assault. He gave no report of rebelcasualties.   He said the raid was part of an offensive he called ``The armedstruggle for democracy will not be detained.'' He read a communiquethat said the academy, where several hundred recruits are trained,was turning out ``agents of repression.''   The armed forces press office said several buildings in thecomplex were damaged.   An army helicopter gunship arrived shortly after the attack beganand illuminated the area with dozens of red flares.   As they withdrew the guerrillas left mines that were removed bybomb-disposal teams.   Guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front havebeen fighting since 1980 to overthrow the government. It isestimated that about 70,000 people have been killed in the war.   Both the 11-week-old rightist government of President AlfredoCristiani and the rebels have indicated a willingness to beginnegotiations on ending the conflict but no peace talks are scheduled.</TEXT></DOC>